quest_title: The loss in weight of a solid when immersed in a liquid at 0\({}^{o}\)c is w\({}_{o}\) and at t\({}^{o}\)c it is w. If the cubical expansivity of solid and liquid are \(\mathrm{\gamma }\)\({}_{s}\) and \(\mathrm{\gamma }\)\({}_{l}\) respectively then w is equal to
explanation_txt:
\(\cfrac{\text { loss in wt at } t^{o} c}{\text { loss in wt at } 0^{\circ} \mathrm{c}}=\cfrac{\text { upthrust at } t^{\circ} \mathrm{C}}{\text { upthrust at } 0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}}\)

\(\text { or, } \cfrac{w}{w_{o}}=\cfrac{v_{b}^{t} \rho_{l}^{t} g}{v_{b}^{0} \rho_{l}^{0} g} =\cfrac{v_{b}^{0}\left(1+\gamma_{s} t\right) \rho_{l}^{0}}{v_{b}^{0} \rho_{l}^{0}\left(1+\gamma_{l} t\right)} =\cfrac{1+\gamma_{s} t}{1+\gamma_{l} t}\)

\(=\left(1+\gamma_{s} t\right)\left(1-\gamma_{l} t\right)\)

\(\begin{aligned} \therefore \mathrm{w} &=\mathrm{w}_{0}\left(1+\gamma_{\mathrm{s}} \mathrm{t}-\gamma_{1} \mathrm{t}\right) \\ &=\mathrm{w}_{\mathrm{o}}\left\{1+\mathrm{t}\left(\gamma_{\mathrm{s}}-\gamma_{l}\right)\right\} \end{aligned}\)

Fundamental frequency of open pipe

\(\mathrm{f}=\cfrac{v}{2 l}=300 \mathrm{Hz}\)

First over tone of open pipe

\(\mathrm{f}_{1}=2 \mathrm{f}_{1}=2 \times 300=600 \mathrm{Hz}\)

first over tone of closed pipe, \(\mathrm{f}_{1}^{\prime}=3 \cdot \cfrac{v}{4 l^{\prime}}\)

According to question,
